@node History "History"

· @{b}v1.10@{ub} - Second Release (27th March 1996)

   - Fixed numerous Enforcer Hits.
   - Everyday.library now translates year numbers of less than 1000 as year numbers for the current century. It used to only work for 1900s and on numbers less than 100 (everything else was compatable for 2000+).
   - Was a bit slack in the minumum Gregorian/Julian day checking department. Everyday.library now only allows dates greater than 14th October 1852. Previously it allowed any day in 1582.
   - Fixed 'Clear List' and 'Run New Script' Menu key short-cuts clash ('X').
   - Altered template for ARexx command @{"GetField" link RX_GetField} from 'NUMBER/N' to 'ENTRY/N/K,NUMBER/N'
   - Fixed CON: de-allocation for ARexx messages.
   - Added 'DROP_SCRIPT' icon tooltype.
   - Tampered with Date Object drag & drop so you can't drag them onto objects with the same attribute values.

° @{b}v1.0@{ub} - Original Release (8th February 1996)

@endnode

@remark ************************************************************
@remark                   ARexx Commands Start Here
@remark ************************************************************

@node ARexxScripts

	@{u}User-Definable ARexx Scripts@{uu}

On-Time allows you to execute external ARexx scripts from within the program. In which case you must have ARexx operational on your system (refer Amiga manuals). On-Time will not execute the scripts itself but tell ARexx to perform the scripts (standard procedure). The essential difference is that the default Host Port for the script will be On-Time.

In the ARexx pull-down menu you will find the following items.

@{b}Run New Script...@{ub}

A file requester will open. Select an ARexx script and close the requester. The file will be executed as an ARexx script.

@{b}Run Last Script@{ub}

This calls the script previously invoked with the 'Run New Script' menu command. If no ARexx script exists then a file requester will open.

@{b}Install ARexx Script (1 to 4)...@{ub}

These four menu items are where you can 'install' four different ARexx scripts. They can then be called quickly via the menu or menu shortcut key.

After selecting one of the four menu items, a file requester will open and you can select the script to install. The script will not be performed at this stage. Now, if you look at the menu item again, you will notice that the previous text has been replaced with the name of the file you selected. The file will appear without it's path name.

@{b}Clear Script...@{ub}

This menu command allows you to remove one of the scripts you previously installed with the 'Install ARexx Script' command. A requester will appear, showing all the currently installed scripts. Just select the one to remove and it will dissappear from the ARexx pull-down menu. Of course the script itself will not be deleted, just the reference to it.

The four scripts installed will be saved as Tooltypes in the On-Time icon when you save the Configuration (not the Event list!). 

You may invoke the execution of one of the four scripts via ARexx as well. See @{"RX command" link RX_RX}.
@endnode

@node ARexxCommands "ARexx Command Set."

	@{u}ARexx Command Set.@{uu}

There can be only one copy of OnTime running at once and its ARexx port is ONTIME.

Apart from the built in MUI ARexx commands (see MUI documentation) there are many others to help you control OnTime.
The commands return their result in the ARexx RESULT variable. Any errors will be reported in the RC variable (0 = success, any other value indicates an error).

@{fg highlight}- A -@{fg text}
@{"About"       link RX_About}       (NO ARGS)
@{"Active"      link RX_Active}      ENTRY/N,NOACTIVE/S

@{fg highlight}- C -@{fg text}
@{"CalDate"     link RX_CalDate}     STRING
@{"CalToday"    link RX_CalToday}    (NO ARGS)
@{"CleanupList" link RX_CleanupList} (NO ARGS)
@{"ClearList"   link RX_ClearList}   (NO ARGS)

@{fg highlight}- G -@{fg text}
@{"GetActive"   link RX_GetActive}   (NO ARGS)
@{"GetCalDate"  link RX_GetCalDate}  FORMAT/K,JULIAN/S
@{"GetEntries"  link RX_GetEntries}  (NO ARGS)
@{"GetField"    link RX_GetField}    ENTRY/N/K,NUMBER/N
@{"GetSelect"   link RX_Select}   ACTIVE/S

@{fg highlight}- L -@{fg text}
@{"LastSaved"   link RX_LastSaved}   (NO ARGS)
@{"List"        link RX_List}        NUMBER/N,TODAY/S
@{"ListFormat"  link RX_ListFormat}  FORMAT/F

@{fg highlight}- O -@{fg text}
@{"Open"        link RX_Open}        FILE,MERGE/S

@{fg highlight}- P -@{fg text}
@{"PutField"    link RX_PutField}    NUMBER/N,VALUE/F/A

@{fg highlight}- R -@{fg text}
@{"Remove"      link RX_Remove}      (NO ARGS)
@{"Restore"     link RX_Restore}     (NO ARGS)
@{"RX"             link RX_RX}             FILE,SCRIPT/N/K

@{fg highlight}- S -@{fg text}
@{"Save"        link RX_Save}        (NO ARGS)
@{"SaveAs"      link RX_SaveAs}      FILE,ICON/S
@{"Search"      link RX_Search}      CASESENS/S,FIELD/N/K,STRING/F/A
@{"Select"      link RX_Select}      ENTRY/N,NOSELECT/S

@{fg highlight}- T -@{fg text}
@{"Toggle"      link RX_Toggle}      (NO ARGS)

@{fg highlight}- U -@{fg text}
@{"Update"      link RX_Update}      (NO ARGS)
@{"UpdateList"  link RX_UpdateList}  (NO ARGS)
@{"Use"         link RX_Use}         (NO ARGS)
@endnode

@node RX_About

@{b}About@{ub}

Purpose: Display the About requester.

Syntax : About (no parameters)

Example: about
@endnode

@node RX_Active

@{b}Active@{ub}

Purpose: Set the active entry in the list.
         The data fields will be updated as well.

Syntax : Active ENTRY/N,NOACTIVE/S

ENTRY/N    - The number of the entry.
NOACTIVE/S - Flag to de-activate the list (eg. no entry active). All data fields will be cleared.

Example: active
@endnode

@node RX_CalDate

@{b}CalDate@{ub}

Purpose: Interpret a string as a Calendar Date. If the date is legal then the Calendar will update just as though you had typed it in manually. Otherwise the Result string will be non-NULL, describing the error.
         No RC variable set.
         
Syntax : CalDate STRING

STRING - Any @{"valid" link Dates} form of date.

Example: CalDate 31
         CalDate 19.2.70
         CalDate 19 F 1970
         CalDate 2440637
@endnode

@node RX_CalToday

@{b}CalToday@{ub}

Purpose: Set the Calendar to the current System (computer) Date.

Syntax : CalToday (no parameters)

Example: caltoday
@endnode

@node RX_CleanupList

@{b}CleanupList@{ub}

Purpose: Perform the CleanupList function where all OLD *non*-repeating events are deleted.
         (Acts on all Events in Main List).
         
Syntax : CleanupList (no parameters)

Example: cleanuplist
@endnode

@node RX_ClearList

@{b}ClearList@{ub}

Purpose: Remove all events from the current list.
         (Acts on all Events in Main List).

Syntax : ClearList (no parameters)

Example: clearlist
@endnode

@node RX_GetActive

@{b}GetActive@{ub}

Purpose: Return the number of the active entry in the Active List.
         Use the @{"List" link RX_List} command to change the Active List.

Syntax : GetActive (no parameters)

Example: getactive
         active = result
@endnode

@node RX_GetCalDate

@{b}GetCalDate@{ub}

Purpose: Return the current Calendar Date.

Syntax : GetCalDate FORMAT/K,JULIAN/S

FORMAT - A Locale specified format. Obviously time formats are irrelevant.
         See the Alarmist Clock Configuration @{"documentation" link "HELP:english/alarmist.guide/ClockFormatting"}.
         One thing to note here: If the Calendar date is before 1st Jan 1978 then the OS routine for Locale formatting cannot handle it. In this case a NULL string will be returned.

If you supply no arguments with this command then it will return the date in the format specified by the OnTime configuration (d/m/y, m/d/y or y/m/d).

Example: getcaldate
         getcaldate julian
         getcaldate %d
@endnode

@node RX_GetEntries

@{b}GetEntries@{ub}

Purpose: Return the current number of entries in the Active List.
         Use the @{"List" link RX_List} command to change the Active list.

Syntax : GetEntries (no parameters)

Example: getentries
         entries = result
@endnode

@node RX_GetField

@{b}GetField@{ub}

Purpose: Return the contents of a data field from a specific entry or the active entry in the list.
         
Syntax : GetField ENTRY/N/K,NUMBER/N

ENTRY/N/K - Number of the entry in the list (1 to Entries) to get info on. If you do not specify ENTRY then the current Active entry will be used.
NUMBER/N  - The number of the field to return.

The following are the field numbers:

   1 - Name
   2 - Date (##:##:####)
   3 - Time (##:##aa)
   4 - Type (1 = Time event, 2 = Day event)
   5 - Notes
   6 - State (0 = off, 1 = on)

More Field variables may be added in the future if the need arises.

Example: getfield 2 /* get field number 2 of the active entry in the list*/
         name = result
         
         getfield entry 5 2 /* get field number 2 of list entry 5 */
         date = result
@endnode

@node RX_GetSelect

@{b}GetSelect@{ub}

Purpose: Return selection state of and entry or the entire (Active) List.
         Use the @{"List" link RX_List} command to change the Active List.

Syntax : Select ACTIVE/S

ACTIVE/S - Return the state of the currently active entry in the list.
           (0 = not selected, 1 = selected)
           
         Without the ACTIVE switch this function will return the number of selected entries in the list.

Example: getselect active
         getselect
@endnode

@node RX_LastSaved

@{b}LastSaved@{ub}

Purpose: Perform the normal LastSaved operation.
         Restore the Event List to previous settings in ENVARC:

Syntax : LastSaved (no parameters)

Example: lastsaved
@endnode

@node RX_List
@{b}List@{ub}

Purpose: Make one of the Lists active (displayed one).

Syntax : List NUMBER/N,TODAY/S

NUMBER - Number of the list to be displayed:
           0      - Main List (containing all Events).
           1 to 7 - Weekday Lists.

TODAY  - Sets the Calendar Date to the System (computer's) date and then makes the weekday corresponding List Active.

Example: list 0
@endnode

@node RX_ListFormat

@{b}ListFormat@{ub}

Purpose: Set the format for the Main List.

Syntax : ListFormat FORMAT/F

FORMAT/F - A set of MUI column format commands.
           For some reason only the Column format commands work.
           
           see @{u}List Format@{uu} in the @{"Config Window" link ConfigWindow}.
           
         
Example: listformat 'col=0,col=5,col=2'
         listformat ',,,'
         listformat ''
@endnode

@node RX_Open

@{b}Open@{ub}

Purpose: Load an OnTime data file.

Syntax : Open FILE,MERGE/S

FILE    - Full name and path of the file to be loaded.
MERGE/S - Flag to cause @{"Merge-Loading" link FileAction}.

Example: open 'ram:YourEvents.list' merge
@endnode

@node RX_PutField

@{b}PutField@{ub}

Purpose: Replace one of the current Event's fields.
         This also simulates the effect of pressing return afterwards.

Syntax : PutField NUMBER/N,VALUE/F/A

NUMBER/N  - The field to act on.

The following are the field numbers:

   1 - Name
   2 - Date
   3 - Type (0 = Time type, 1 = Day type)
   4 - Time
   5 - Repeat Day
   6 - Repeat Month
   7 - Repeat Year
   8 - Reminder Days
   9 - Notes
  10 - State (0 = off, 1 = on)

VALUE/F/A - The string to put in the specified field.
            You should use this argument(s) last and use the command 'VALUE' before hand.
            The rest of the line after the command is used as the string, so spaces are allowed.

Example: 'putfield 1 value=Birthday: Me'
         'putfield 2 value=19 feb 70'
         'putfield 3 value=1'

This is the standard way of entering Event data via ARexx.
If you wish to insert a new Event then just deselect the list with the 'active noactive' command then proceed to insert data into the fields with the 'putfield' command.
@endnode

@node RX_Remove

@{b}Remove@{ub}

Purpose: Remove all currently selected (or single Active) entries from the Active list.
         Use the @{"List" link RX_List} command to change the Active List.
         
Syntax : Remove (no parameters)

Example: remove

         returns the number of entries removed.
@endnode

@node RX_Restore

@{b}Restore@{ub}

Purpose: Perform the normal Restore operation.
         Restore the Event list to previous settings in ENV:

Syntax : Restore (no parameters)

Example: restore
@endnode

@{b}RX@{ub}

Purpose: Invoke an ARexx script from within OnTime.

Syntax : RX FILE,SCRIPT/N/K

FILE       - Full name of the file to be executed.
SCRIPT/N/K - The number of a previously installed @{"ARexx Script" link ARexxScripts} to be executed.

Example: rx 'rexx:test_script.rexx'
         rx script 2
@endnode

@node RX_Save

@{b}Save@{ub}

Purpose: This command performs the same function as the 'Save' button in the Main Window.

Syntax : Save (no parameters)

Example: save
@endnode

@node RX_SaveAs

@{b}SaveAs@{ub}

Purpose: Save the list using a specified filename.

Syntax : SaveAs FILE,ICON/S

FILE   - The new file name.
ICON/S - Flag to indicate whether a 'presets' icon is to be created for this saved file.

Example: saveas "ram:backup.list" icon
@endnode

@node RX_Search

@{b}Search@{ub}

Purpose: @{"Search" link Searching} for a string in the contents of the Active List.
         If a match is found then this list entry will become active.
         Use the @{"List" link RX_List} command to change the Active List.

Syntax : Search CASESENS/S,FIELD/N/K,STRING/F/A

CASESENS/S - Flag to cause a case sensitive (exact case matching) search.
FIELD/N/K  - Number to indicate what field(s) to search.
STRING/F/A - An AmigaDOS search pattern.

   The field numbering is as follows:
   
   0 - All the following fields
   1 - Event Name
   2 - Event Date
   3 - Event Time
   4 - Event Notes
   
Example: search #?birthday#? field 0
@endnode

@node RX_Select

@{b}Select@{ub}

Purpose: Cause an entry in the Active List to become selected (does not activate it).
         Use the @{"List" link RX_List} command to change the Active List.

Syntax : Select ENTRY/N,NOSELECT/S

ENTRY/N    - Number of the entry in the list to select.
NOSELECT/S - Flag to deselect ALL entries in the list.

Example: select 5
         select no select
@endnode

@node RX_Toggle

@{b}Toggle@{ub}

Purpose: Toggle the active state of all currently selected (or single Active) entries in Active List.
         Use the @{"List" link RX_List} command to change the Active List.
         
Syntax : Toggle (no parameters)

Example: toggle
@endnode

@node RX_Update

@{b}Update@{ub}

Purpose: Re-Analyse system time and reset calendar to this date.
         If you were more interested in updating the list you could send a 'Restore' or 'LastSaved' command then OnTime will be fully up-to-date.


Syntax : Update (no parameters)

Example: update
@endnode

@node RX_UpdateList

@{b}UpdateList@{ub}

Purpose: Perform the UpdateList function where all OLD *repeating* events are updated.

Syntax : UpdateList (no parameters)

Example: updatelist
@endnode

@node RX_Use

@{b}Use@{ub}

Purpose: This command performs the same function as the 'Use' button in the Main Window.

Syntax : Use (no parameters)

Example: use
@endnode

